 SIGNALS\n\n**NASDAQ** futures positioning is the most structurally fragile setup. Hedge funds are at the 10th percentile net short (52-week basis), having added aggressively to shorts over the past month (-6pp net/OI). Meanwhile, dealers are at the 92nd percentile net long \u2014 absorbing the sell flow. The top-8 short concentration has surged +9.6pp over the month, meaning a handful of players now dominate the short side. With NASDAQ +6.8% on the week, this is a classic short-squeeze setup. The fragility here is that any sustained rally forces crowded shorts to cover, amplifying moves. That said, futures positioning captures only part of institutional equity exposure \u2014 qualify accordingly.\n\n**US10Y** Treasuries show a high-conviction structural long from asset managers (77th percentile) offset by hedge funds at the 81st percentile *net short* \u2014 one of the largest HF short positions in the past year. Dealers are at the 4th percentile net short, meaning they are warehousing significant long client flow. The AM/HF divergence here is genuine: AMs are expressing duration as a recession hedge; HFs are positioned for yields to stay elevated or rise. One side will be forced to capitulate. Given OI fell 5% over the month, some position reduction is already occurring.\n\n**CAD** long concentration has surged dramatically \u2014 top-4 traders now hold 54.8% of long OI, up 16pp in a month. HFs are near 52-week short extremes (23rd pctl). This is a highly concentrated, potentially illiquid setup.\n\n---\n\n## 3. CROSS-INSTRUMENT THEMES\n\nThe HF short bias runs consistently across **US10Y**, **NASDAQ**, and **CAD** \u2014 a coherent \"risk-off, higher-for-longer\" macro view. Yet equity prices rallied sharply this week, directly contradicting that positioning. Meanwhile, **1-Month US** AM positioning is at the 94th percentile long \u2014 consistent with cash-hoarding or flight-to-safety at the front end, not rate-cut positioning. **YEN** short concentration on the sell side is building (+8.8pp 8-trader short concentration over a month), suggesting the yen carry unwind thesis remains live.\n\n---\n\n## 4. KEY RISKS\n\n- **NASDAQ/SP500 short squeeze acceleration**: HF shorts are crowded and concentrated; a continued equity rally could trigger disorderly covering, amplified by thin liquidity in the short book\n- **US10Y dislocation**: If AMs are forced to reduce duration (e.g., liability-driven selling, margin calls), the HF short thesis gets validated violently \u2014 watch dealer positioning as the stress indicator\n- **CAD long concentration unwind**: With 4 traders controlling 55% of the long side, any reversal of CAD flows could be disorderly and fast"}